awards: [{'title': 'Master Thesis Award 2013', 'description': 'The Nalacs Thesis Award 2013 was presented to Karolien van Teijlingen for her thesis entitled "Negotiating values and development at the mining frontier: Private, public, and civil interactions over El Mirador mine in South-East Ecuador". The jury has praised the thesis for giving such an impressive, nuanced and subtle analysis on the strategic use of discourses in relation to development, territory and nature-society relations in South-East Ecuador. By combining insightful theoretical reflections on environmental conflicts in Ecuador with beautiful ethnographic data on the way the “struggle over meaning” is shaped at the mining frontier, Karolien has made a great contribution to the current academic and societal debates on the relationship between the mining industry and sustainable development in Latin America and beyond.\n\nNALACS has instituted a prize for the best MA thesis on the region written at a Dutch university. Important criteria in evaluating the theses are: Scientific quality and originality, Writing style and structure of the thesis and Societal relevance. The jury for this year’s thesis award consisted of Dr. Griet Steel (IOB, University of Antwerp), Daphne Roodhuyzen, MSc (HIVOS) and Dr. Marc Simon Thomas (Utrecht University).
